    </div>
    <h1>Boosted Post</h1>
    <p class="description">An existing organic social post you promote with paid budget to extend reach. Typical CPM is <strong>$1-$5 per 1,000 impressions</strong>, and results start at $5/day.</p>
    <div class="post-meta">
      <div class="meta-author">
        <div class="meta-avatar">AVR</div>
        <div class="meta-author-info">
          <span class="meta-author-name"><a href="/authors/akshay-vr/">Akshay VR</a></span>
          <span class="meta-author-role">Marketing Head · theStacc</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Published</span><span class="meta-value">Jul 2026</span></div>
      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Read</span><span class="meta-value">6 min</span></div>
      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">Promoted post · Post boost</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>boosted post</strong> is an existing organic social media post that you promote with paid advertising budget to extend its reach beyond your current followers. Unlike a <a href="/glossary/dark-post/">dark post</a> created solely as an ad, a boosted post <strong>stays permanently on your profile</strong> and keeps its organic likes, comments, and shares while gaining paid distribution.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Typical CPM</div>
            <div class="tms-value">$1\u2013$5 / 1,000 imps</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Min daily spend</div>
            <div class="tms-value">$5\u2013$20</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Boosting is social's lowest-friction paid entry point. It works best when you use it deliberately \u2014 amplifying content that has already earned engagement \u2014 and stops working the moment you use it as a bulk substitute for real ad campaigns.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a boosted post?</h2>
        <p>A boosted post is an organic post \u2014 image, video, carousel, reel \u2014 that you promote with paid ad spend on Facebook, Instagram, LinkedIn, TikTok, or X. The setup is deliberately simplified: select the post, choose an audience, set a budget, pick a duration. The platform handles targeting and delivery. The post itself remains on your profile with its organic engagement intact while paid distribution runs alongside.</p>
        <p>Boosts sit at the entry level of the platform's paid tools \u2014 above pure organic reach, below full <a href="/glossary/paid-social/">paid social</a> campaigns run in <a href="/glossary/meta-ads-manager/">Meta Ads Manager</a>, LinkedIn Campaign Manager, or TikTok Ads Manager.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why boosting exists</div>
          <p><a href="/glossary/organic-reach/">Organic reach</a> on Meta platforms has collapsed to under 5% of a page's followers. A boosted post is the platforms' way of monetizing that decline \u2014 the fastest, lowest-effort route to putting a post in front of the followers that never see your organic content, plus a broader interest audience.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why boosted posts matter</h2>
        <p>Boosting is not a full <a href="/glossary/social-media-marketing/">social media marketing</a> strategy, but it earns its place for four reasons:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Amplify proven content.</strong> Content that already earned organic engagement is your least risky paid bet.</li>
          <li><strong>Zero ad manager expertise required.</strong> Any page admin can boost \u2014 no campaign structure, ad sets, or creatives to build.</li>
          <li><strong>Affordable brand awareness.</strong> $1-$5 CPM makes it the cheapest paid impression class on most platforms.</li>
          <li><strong>Testing ground.</strong> Cheap way to see which content resonates before committing budget to a full campaign.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How boosted posts work</h2>
        <p>The workflow is roughly identical across platforms: pick a winner, define who, define how much, watch the numbers.</p>
        <h3>Step 1 \u2014 Pick a high-performing organic post</h3>
        <p>Do not boost every post. Boost the ones with above-average engagement rate, click-throughs, or comments. Engagement predicts paid performance.</p>
        <h3>Step 2 \u2014 Configure the audience</h3>
        <p>Options include: your followers, followers plus lookalike, custom targeting by location and demographics, or a saved audience from your ads manager. For local businesses, geographic + interest targeting works best.</p>
        <h3>Step 3 \u2014 Set budget and duration</h3>
        <p>Start with $5-$20 daily over 3-7 days. This range gives the algorithm enough delivery to learn while keeping cost per test contained.</p>
        <h3>Step 4 \u2014 Monitor results</h3>
        <p>Platforms show <a href="/glossary/impressions/">impressions</a>, reach, <a href="/glossary/engagement-rate/">engagement</a>, link clicks, and cost per result. Kill boosts that spike CPM or underperform CTR benchmarks within 48 hours.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Boost vs ad vs dark post \u2014 the paid social hierarchy</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Format</th><th>Where it lives</th><th>Targeting depth</th><th>Best for</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Boosted post</strong></td><td>On your profile</td><td>Basic (location, demo, interests)</td><td>Amplifying proven organic content</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Full ad campaign</td><td>In feeds only \u2014 or on profile</td><td>Full (custom, lookalike, retargeting)</td><td>Conversion, lead gen, retargeting</td></tr>
              <tr><td><a href="/glossary/dark-post/">Dark post</a></td><td>Feed only, not on profile</td><td>Full ad-manager options</td><td>A/B testing creative variants</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Organic post</td><td>On your profile</td><td>Followers only</td><td>Community, evergreen content</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real boosted post examples</h2>
        <h3>1. Dental practice with a $30 Instagram boost</h3>
        <p>A dental practice boosted an Instagram post showing before-and-after teeth whitening photos. A $30 boost over 5 days generated 8,000 impressions, 240 profile visits, and 3 direct-message appointment requests. Cost per booking under $10.</p>
        <h3>2. B2B company with $100 LinkedIn boost</h3>
        <p>A B2B SaaS boosted a founder's LinkedIn post about their latest product feature. A $100 boost reached 15,000 relevant professionals, generated 60 profile visits, and produced 4 demo requests. Cost per demo under $25.</p>
        <h3>3. Local retail using boosted reels</h3>
        <p>A boutique boutique boosted a reel of new arrivals to a 10-mile radius audience. $50 delivered 24,000 views, 300 saves, and a 40% lift in in-store foot traffic that week.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Boosted post vs full ad campaign \u2014 when to use which</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use a boost when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Content already has strong organic engagement</li>
              <li>Objective is awareness, engagement, or profile visits</li>
              <li>You have $5-$500 to spend</li>
              <li>You don\u2019t need retargeting or conversion tracking</li>
              <li>Setup speed matters more than optimization depth</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use a full ad campaign when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Objective is conversions or lead generation</li>
              <li>You need advanced targeting (custom audiences, lookalikes)</li>
              <li>Budget exceeds $500 total</li>
              <li>You need A/B tests across creative variants</li>
              <li>Retargeting and pixel-driven optimization matter</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 boosted post best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Only boost proven content.</strong> Wait 48-72 hours after publishing to see organic performance before deciding what to boost.</li>
          <li><strong>Match audience to content.</strong> A humorous post to a warm audience; an educational post to cold interest targeting.</li>
          <li><strong>Cap boost duration at 7 days.</strong> Frequency fatigue sets in fast. Stop and restart with a new creative if you want longer runs.</li>
          <li><strong>Include a clear call-to-action.</strong> Boosts without a next step (visit, DM, click) waste the reach.</li>
          <li><strong>Track cost per result, not vanity impressions.</strong> A cheap CPM does not mean a cheap conversion.</li>
          <li><strong>Graduate to ad campaigns above $500.</strong> The boost interface caps your optimization ability. Larger spends deserve better tooling.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap \u2014 boosting every post equally</div>
          <p>Splitting a $500 monthly budget into $50 boosts across 10 posts almost always underperforms putting the full $500 behind the single best-performing post plus a proper campaign structure. Boost the winners, not the average.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common boosted post mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Boosting weak organic performers.</strong> Paid distribution amplifies whatever's already there \u2014 including boring content.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring frequency.</strong> The same audience seeing the same post 10 times reduces engagement per impression.</li>
          <li><strong>Using boosts for conversions.</strong> Conversion campaigns need the deeper optimization only the ad manager provides.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping audience targeting.</strong> "Boost to my followers" often wastes spend on people who would see the post organically anyway.</li>
          <li><strong>Not measuring cost per outcome.</strong> Reach without conversion is impressions without value.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">What is the difference between a boosted post and an ad?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>A boosted post starts as an organic post visible on your profile that you promote with paid budget \u2014 it stays on your feed with all its likes and comments. A dark post or ad is created inside the ad manager, doesn't appear on your profile, and unlocks advanced targeting, placement, and objective options a boost cannot access.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">How much should you spend on boosted posts?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Start with $5-$20 daily for testing. Most small businesses see meaningful results between $50-$200 per post, focused on content that already has strong organic engagement. Above ~$500, switching to full ad campaigns typically outperforms boosting for the same spend.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">Are boosted posts worth it?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes for brand awareness, local reach, and amplifying proven organic content. No for conversion campaigns, retargeting, or complex funnels \u2014 those need the deeper targeting and optimization controls of an ad manager.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">Can I boost any post?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Most organic posts can be boosted, but platforms block boosts for posts violating policy \u2014 restricted categories (housing, employment, politics on Meta), copyright issues, or posts with excessive text on images.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">Which posts should I boost?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Boost posts already outperforming your average organic engagement \u2014 that signal predicts paid performance too. Testimonials, case studies, product demos, and educational videos usually boost well; sale announcements and generic promotions rarely do.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

